  "prompt": "What kind of first jobs do neuroscience majors tend to get?",
  "response": "Neuroscience majors typically start their careers in various fields, including:\n\n1. Research positions\n- Research assistant in academic or medical laboratories\n- Clinical research coordinator\n- Laboratory technician\n\n2. Healthcare-related roles\n- Medical or pharmaceutical sales\n- Clinical data analyst\n- Healthcare research assistant\n- Medical scribe\n\n3. Entry-level positions in neuroscience-related industries\n- Pharmaceutical research assistant\n- Medical device company research associate\n- Neurotechnology startup roles\n\n4. Graduate school preparation\n- Post-baccalaureate research assistant\n- Lab technician while applying to graduate or medical school\n\n5. Mental health support roles\n- Mental health technician\n- Behavioral health assistant\n- Psychiatric rehabilitation specialist\n\n6. Education and science communication\n- Science teacher\n- Education coordinator\n- Science writer or communicator\n\n7. Administrative roles in research institutions\n- Clinical trial coordinator\n- Grant management assistant\n- Research administration\n\nThe specific job often depends on individual interests, additional skills, internship experiences, and whether the graduate plans to pursue advanced degrees like a Ph.D. or medical degree.",
